"{\n  \"text\": \"Hey everybody. Today I want to show you how I plant my seeds and how much fun it is. So the first thing I do is I get a bucket of dirt from my worm pile. So this is where I cure my compost. And the first thing I do is take all the debris and the wood chips and all the rough stuff that's on top because in the worm pile, all the big stuff goes to the top and all the little stuff falls down as the chickens move it and the rain and the wind and all that kind of disturbs it. And then uh once I get down to that good layer, I shovel it into a bucket, and this is what it looks like. Oh, it's great. I have great dirt uh soil. And then I come over here, and this is what my bed looks like. It's full of that rough debris that I just scraped off because I don't get all of it, and so I have to go through and scrape off the top again because all the big pieces come to the top. And if I leave them there, it it's not a problem at all, they'll all break down slowly. Uh, but the big chunks rise to the top and then it prevents good seeding, which I'm about to do. So I take my little hand rake, which is a rake where the handle fell off, and I just uh basically take off uh all of the big chunks by strafing the surface. This doesn't kill the grass or anything, but it kind of takes all the loose stuff up, and this is what it looks like after I'm done strafing. It's a lot cleaner, uh a lot finer. So then I'm ready to add my seeds. Here I go, adding all a bunch of seeds. I think this was um a lettuce, uh uh seeded black lettuce that I enjoy. So I'm planting all these seeds, and then when I'm done, I'm gonna take that soil that I just uh got from the uh worm pile, and I'm going to spread this thinly over to cover the seeds I just put down. This is just as easier a way than kind of digging them up, and I need to add soil periodically throughout the garden to replenish the organic matter in there anyway, add more humus. And so that's what I do every time I seed. I just add the the bucket there and I'm all done. Now I need to go back and cut up some of this grass and other stuff because I'm making room for my plants. And I don't uproot the the plants. I never do that because that disturbs the crumb structure of your soil. And also the microbes really enjoy eating those roots. And so uh I'll cut all this back, some of it will come back, most of it will die, and then I'll water this whole thing. I put a couple, I get some legumes. I have a little patch of legumes, and I add that to the grasses to help it break down, and then I water everything. And after I'm all finished watering it up and giving it a good soaking, distributed the last bit of it. This is what it looks like. It's all flattened out and the soil is fine and seated and ready to go. Oh man, how much fun is this? Anyway, thanks y'all. Appreciate it.\",\n  \"sentences\": [\n    {\n      \"text\": \" Hey everybody.\",\n      \"start\": 0.4,\n      \"end\": 1.6,\n      \"duration\": 1.2,\n      \"confidence\": 0.977,\n      \"tokens\": [\n        {\n          \"text\": \" He\",\n          \"start\": 0.4,\n          \"end\": 0.64,\n          \"duration\": 0.24,\n          \"confidence\": 0.993\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"y\",\n          \"start\": 0.64,\n          \"end\": 0.8,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \" ever\",\n          \"start\": 0.88,\n          \"end\": 1.04,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"yb\",\n          \"start\": 1.04,\n          \"end\": 1.28,\n          \"duration\": 0.24,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"ody\",\n          \"start\": 1.28,\n          \"end\": 1.44,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \".\",\n          \"start\": 1.44,\n          \"end\": 1.6,\n          \"duration\": 0.